-1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 229 "2.  Polynomials:  Intercepts a
nd Sign.  There are several features about the graphs of polynomials w
hich are important to track.  These features inform us about the behav
ior of the function.  Those features include the following:" }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 57 "    a.    x-int
ercepts of the function                   " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 129 "                       Those values where the graph crosses th
e x-axis.  Those points are solutions of the equation y = f(x) = 0." }
}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 105 "    b.    regions (intervals) in the do
main of the function where the values of the function are positive" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 215 "                       Those regions whe
re the graph lies above the x-axis.  For a continuous function, and in
 particular for polynomials, these regions are bounded by the intercep
ts and may stretch to +/- infinity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 105 " \+
   c.    regions (intervals) in the domain of the function where the v
alues of the function are negative" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 215 "  \+
                     Those regions where the graph lies below the x-ax
is.  For a continuous function, and in particular for polynomials, the
se regions are bounded by the intercepts and may stretch to +/- infini
ty." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 36 "    d.   y-intercept of the functi
on" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 107 "                       The value w
here the graph crosses the y-axis.  The value of the function when x =
 0." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 19 "    e.   end limits" }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 384 "                       For a polynomial, its values
 will become either arbitrarily large in a positive sense or arbitrari
ly large in a negative sense as the domain values tend to infinity.  G
raphically, the values on the graph will growth arbitrarily large posi
tively (go up off the graph) or arbitrarily large negative (go down of
f the graph) as the domain values tend to infinity.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 
"" {TEXT -1 87 "                       Similar behavior holds true for
 approaches to negative infinity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 150 "For each of the following polynomials,  \+
provide a graph of the polynomial.  Choose a range that will optimally
 represent the features of the graph.   " }{TEXT 268 4 "Also" }{TEXT 
-1 90 ", for each polynomial find each of the above five graphcial cha
racteristics (a.  thru e.):" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 5 "a.   " }{MPLTEXT 0 21 16 "y = 6*x^2+24*x-8" }}
